Title: Background-Timer Plugin Dispatch Crosses In-Process Service Boundary Without Scope Binding
Severity-Original: HIGH
Phase: 8
Class: transitive-trust
Edge-ID: E004
Producer: plugin-runtime:src/gateway/server-plugins.ts:297-339 (dispatchGatewayMethod)
Consumer: gateway:src/gateway/server-methods.ts:58 (authorizeGatewayMethod)
Channel: ipc (in-process dispatchGatewayMethod with syntheticClient fallback)
Verdict: VALID
Debate:
  Team-01 PH-CF-04 flagged timer-bypass as a causal-followup hypothesis, not a validated finding.
  Phase 8 promotes this to VALID with cross-service evidence: the mechanism is E004 (dispatchGatewayMethod
  fallback to syntheticClient when AsyncLocalStorage scope is unset) and the class is transitive-trust
  (gateway trusts that plugin-runtime dispatch always has a scope; it does not when called from timers).
  Concrete impact: plugins executing background tasks (polling, scheduled cleanup, cron-style work)
  can call gateway methods at WRITE_SCOPE with no identity attached; for deleteSession the upgrade
  to ADMIN_SCOPE is unconditional (E003); for other methods the fallback syntheticScopes is WRITE_SCOPE.
Origin-Finding: Team-01 PH-CF-04 (background timer bypasses withPluginRuntimePluginIdScope)
Deep-Probe-Corroboration: authz-matrix A2 Gap A (dispatchGatewayMethod forceSyntheticClient fallback)
