 *      token resolves to OLD_GEN.
 *   5. BUT: a client whose token resolves to NEW_GEN connects, records
 *      sharedGatewaySessionGeneration=NEW_GEN into its GatewayWsClient record
 *      (message-handler.ts:1322) while applyHotReload is still running and
 *      before required is cleared by setCurrentSharedGatewaySessionGeneration
 *      at L544.  disconnectStaleSharedGatewayAuthClients (L522) already ran
 *      against the old client set — this new connection is never in that set
 *      — so it survives even if applyHotReload later fails and the error-
 *      recovery branch resets .current back to the previous generation (L535).
 *   6. After the rollback at L535, getRequiredSharedGatewaySessionGeneration
 *      returns OLD_GEN again, but the survivor's recorded generation is
 *      NEW_GEN; the per-message check at message-handler.ts:1559 will now
 *      reject every subsequent frame on this connection with 4001, but the
 *      IDENTIFY/HELLO exchange already completed — the session is live for
 *      one full request-response cycle.
 *
 * Static-analysis trace
 * ─────────────────────
 * The script below:
 *   A. Reconstructs the state machine in memory using the exact same logic as
 *      the production code (copied verbatim so no harness-skip of controls).
 *   B. Interleaves the two-write sequence with a simulated handshake arriving
 *      in the async gap.
 *   C. Asserts the two exploitable outcomes:
 *      - Outcome 1 (happy-path race): client with NEW_GEN token connects
 *        during the gap, applyHotReload succeeds, required is cleared; client
 *        survives all checks.  This is the nominal "one-frame window" outcome.
 *      - Outcome 2 (rollback race): client with NEW_GEN token connects during
 *        the gap, applyHotReload fails and state rolls back to OLD_GEN;
 *        client's recorded generation is now orphaned and every subsequent
 *        per-message check rejects it — but the initial IDENTIFY frame was
 *        already processed.
