## Draft Finding

---
Title: Plugin subagent `deleteSession` mints ADMIN_SCOPE synthetic client unconditionally
Severity-Original: HIGH
Phase: 6
Class: vertical-escalation
Endpoint: WS `sessions.delete` (via `dispatchGatewayMethod` from plugin subagent runtime)
Handler: src/gateway/server-plugins.ts:443-466
Verdict: VALID
Debate:
Origin-Finding: NEW — Gap A in p2-008 covers the general `createSyntheticOperatorClient` / `syntheticScopes` pattern; this finding extends Gap A with the concrete production call site that unconditionally mints ADMIN_SCOPE for ANY plugin calling `runtime.deleteSession()`.
Deep-Probe-Corroboration: none (Phase 5 not started)
Cross-ref: p2-008 Gap A (`src/gateway/server-plugins.ts:263`, `304-326`); p4-009 (structural params.scopes pattern)
---

## Summary

Any plugin that calls `runtime.subagent.deleteSession()` causes the gateway plugin runtime to call `dispatchGatewayMethod("sessions.delete", ..., { forceSyntheticClient: true, syntheticScopes: [ADMIN_SCOPE] })` at `server-plugins.ts:453-454`. The `forceSyntheticClient: true` flag causes `handleGatewayRequest` to use a freshly-minted `GatewayWsClient` with `role: "operator"` and `scopes: ["operator.admin"]` — regardless of whether the originating request that triggered the plugin had any admin scope. A plugin installed by an operator with only `WRITE_SCOPE`, if it calls `deleteSession` for any session key, will succeed. The blast radius is deletion of any non-main session (main-session protection is enforced inside the handler itself at line 1718-1727), including sessions belonging to other agents.

## Evidence

- Handler: `src/gateway/server-plugins.ts:443-466`
- Relevant code:
  ```ts
  // server-plugins.ts:443-466
  const pluginOwnedCleanupOptions = pluginId
    ? {
        pluginRuntimeOwnerId: pluginId,
        ...(!hasAdminScope(scope?.client)
          ? {
              forceSyntheticClient: true,
              syntheticScopes: [ADMIN_SCOPE],  // <-- unconditional elevation
            }
          : {}),
      }
    : undefined;
  await dispatchGatewayMethod(
    "sessions.delete",
    { key: params.sessionKey, deleteTranscript: params.deleteTranscript ?? true },
    pluginOwnedCleanupOptions,
  );
  ```
- Guard stack observed: `authorizeGatewayMethod` checks the synthetic client's `scopes: [ADMIN_SCOPE]` — passes, because the elevation happens before the chokepoint.
- Object-id parameter: `params.sessionKey` (caller-supplied)
- Ownership clause: `rejectPluginRuntimeDeleteMismatch` checks that the session's `pluginId` matches `client.internal.pluginRuntimeOwnerId` — however, the internal field is set to the calling plugin's ID, and the check only applies when the session entry has a plugin-owned extension record. Sessions without a plugin extension record (e.g., the main agent's non-plugin sessions) are not protected by this check and can be deleted.

## Attack Steps

1. Attacker installs or controls a plugin (or exploits plugin install integrity gap).
2. Plugin calls `runtime.subagent.deleteSession({ sessionKey: "target-session-key" })`.
3. Gateway runtime invokes `dispatchGatewayMethod("sessions.delete", ..., { forceSyntheticClient: true, syntheticScopes: [ADMIN_SCOPE] })`.
4. `handleGatewayRequest` runs with synthetic client bearing `operator.admin` scope.
5. `sessions.delete` handler deletes the session and its transcript.
6. Result: arbitrary non-main session deleted by a plugin with no admin scope in the originating request.

## Why This Passed SAST

The elevation is intentional-looking defensive code ("if the plugin doesn't have admin scope, grant it for cleanup") but the scope of the grant is unconstrained — it applies to any session key the plugin provides, not just sessions the plugin created.

## Recommended Fix

Constrain `sessions.delete` when called via `forceSyntheticClient` to sessions explicitly owned by `pluginRuntimeOwnerId` (extend `rejectPluginRuntimeDeleteMismatch` to cover all sessions, not only plugin-extension-bearing ones). Alternatively, add a flag to mark that the synthetic client may only delete sessions created in the current plugin runtime scope.

## Phase 7 Follow-up

State machine integrity: does `rejectPluginRuntimeDeleteMismatch` cover all session types, or only those with plugin extension records? Phase 7 should verify the guard logic covers the full session-entry universe.

