# p4-002 — SSRF via MINIMAX_API_HOST in minimax-vlm.ts

**Title**: `fetch()` in minimax-vlm.ts uses MINIMAX_API_HOST without fetchWithSsrFGuard
**Class**: SSRF
**Severity-Original**: HIGH
**Verdict**: VALID
**Pre-FP-Flag**: yes (MINIMAX_API_HOST is in BLOCKED_WORKSPACE_DOTENV_KEYS — workspace .env injection mitigated; but host-level env or provider config UI can still set it)

## Evidence

- File: `src/agents/minimax-vlm.ts:89`
- Semgrep rule: `archon.semgrep-rules.direct-fetch-without-ssrf-guard`
- Tool source: custom semgrep

## Details

```typescript
const host = resolveMinimaxHost(params.apiHost ?? process.env.MINIMAX_API_HOST ?? ...);
const url = new URL("/v1/coding_plan/vlm", host).toString();
const res = await fetch(url, { ... });
```

`MINIMAX_API_HOST` is read from `process.env` without SSRF guard. While this key is blocked in workspace `.env` loading, an operator or attacker with env-level access (or legitimate operator config UI) can set it to an internal host (e.g., `http://169.254.169.254/`). `fetchWithSsrFGuard` is not called, so no SSRF policy applies to this request.

## Attacker Control
- Input: `MINIMAX_API_HOST` env var (host env, operator config, or system-level injection)
- Runtime: agent runtime (Node.js)
- Boundary: Agent tool execution → outbound HTTP without SSRF guard

## Effect
SSRF to internal/loopback/metadata services if operator or attacker can set env var (requires elevated position — operator-class or env-level access).

## Enrichment Classification
**likely security** (reduced severity given BLOCKED_WORKSPACE_DOTENV_KEYS) — operator-level attacker can reach internal network

