# p4-001 — TwiML Host Injection via HTTP Host Header

**Title**: TwiML Stream URL constructed from untrusted `req.headers.host`
**Class**: Injection / XSS-adjacent (XML injection into TwiML response)
**Severity-Original**: HIGH
**Verdict**: VALID
**Pre-FP-Flag**: no

## Evidence

- File: `extensions/voice-call/src/webhook/realtime-handler.ts:332`
- Semgrep rule: `javascript.express.security.injection.raw-html-format.raw-html-format`
- Tool source: semgrep (baseline)

## Details

`buildTwiMLPayload` constructs a TwiML XML response using template literals:

```typescript
const host = this.publicOrigin || req.headers.host || DEFAULT_HOST;
const wsUrl = `wss://${host}${this.getStreamPathPattern()}/${token}`;
const twiml = `<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<Response>
  <Connect>
    <Stream url="${wsUrl}" />
  </Connect>
</Response>`;
```

`req.headers.host` is attacker-controlled. If `this.publicOrigin` is not configured (null/empty), `req.headers.host` flows into the XML without escaping. A crafted `Host:` header like `evil.com" onload="...` or XML-special chars could inject arbitrary XML attributes into the TwiML response, redirecting the WebSocket stream to an attacker-controlled host.

## Attacker Control
- Input: HTTP `Host` header on incoming webhook POST
- Runtime: voice-call extension (Node HTTP server)
- Boundary: Internet → Twilio webhook handler → TwiML response read by Twilio

## Effect
If `publicOrigin` is unset (default when operator has not configured a public URL), any caller reaching the webhook can redirect Twilio audio stream connections to an arbitrary WebSocket host — cross-tenant audio exfiltration.

## Enrichment Classification
**likely security** — crosses trust boundary (webhook caller controls response consumed by Twilio)

## CodeQL Reachability
No slice pre-computed; on-demand analysis required.

